    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1915-01-12T19:00:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1915-01-12T19:00:00-05:00" n="449"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d449">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">File No. 763.72112/594</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The <gloss type="from">Secretary of State</gloss> to the
                        Ambassador in Great Britain</hi> (<persName corresp="#p_PWH1" type="to">
                        <hi rend="italic">Page</hi>
                    </persName>)</head>
                <opener>
                    <seg rendition="#center">[Telegram]</seg>
                </opener>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Washington</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1915-01-12T19:00:00-05:00">
                            <hi rend="italic">January 12, 1915, 7 p. m.</hi>
                        </date>
                    </dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>939. Your number 1434, January 7, 8 p. m.<note n="1" xml:id="d449fn1">
                        <hi rend="italic">Ante</hi>, <ref target="#pg_299">p. 299</ref>.</note>
                    Please prepare a note to <persName corresp="#p_GSE1">Sir Edward Grey</persName>
                    in reply to his note of January 7 in the sense of the following:<quote
                        rend="blockquote">
                        <p>We appreciate the friendly spirit in which the American note of December
                                28<note n="2" xml:id="d449fn2">
                                <ref target="frus1914Supp#pg_372">
                                    <hi rend="italic">Foreign Relations</hi>, 1914, Supplement, p.
                                    372</ref>.</note> was received by the British Government and we
                            have no doubt that the cordial relations between the two Governments
                            will continue throughout the pending diplomatic discussion. The
                            Government of the United States notes with satisfaction that His
                            Majesty’s Government agree with the principles of international law as
                            set forth in the American note. As this note is being carefully examined
                            by the British Government with a view to making a further reply in
                            detail, it would seem premature for me to answer at the present time <pb
                                facs="0564" n="306" xml:id="pg_306"/> the remarks of <persName
                                corresp="#p_GSE1">Sir Edward Grey</persName>. It is the intention of
                            this Government to consider the points raised by <persName
                                corresp="#p_GSE1">Sir Edward Grey</persName> in connection with the
                            further reply of the British Government promised by him.</p>
                    </quote>
                </p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <persName corresp="#p_BWJ1">
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Bryan</hi>
                        </persName>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
    </text>
